newsitem.title: USA: CME lumber ends mostly lower, Sep sets new high.
newsitem.headline: CME lumber ends mostly lower, Sep sets new high.

text.p: CME lumber futures ended mostly lower but the strong tone to cash lumber prices boosted September to a new contract high of $414.50 per tbf, marking the highest level in 2-1/2 years, traders said.

September reached the highest price since March 11, 1994, before closing $3.00 per tbf higher at $413.90. Other months finished $0.20 to $1.70 lower on profit taking and bull spreading with November off the least at $371.20 after also setting a new contract high early of $373.70.
Cash markets have been climbing recently on concern over hurricanes which could hit the U.S. East Coast, as well as on tight lumber supplies.

"Hurricanes are stacked up like bowling balls out there" in the Atlantic, said Jim Elrod, trader with Pacific Futures Trading. He added that technicals are also very strong. Charts point to September going up to the $425 to $430 area, double of the hight of the April/July double bottom, he said.
Cash sources put spruce prices in the $420 or higher area, up from Friday's official quote of $414 per tbf.
